Date: Tue, 10 Feb 1998 23:42:07 +1300
From: E. Ravji <boss@clear.net.nz>
Source: The Southland Times - February 10, 1998 [edited

Department of Conservation (DOC) staff are expecting the first results of
tests carried out at Massey University on tissue samples from dead sea
lions soon. DOC sea lion expert Mike Donoghue said tissue samples were
rushed to Rotterdam at the weekend. Testing would be carried out by a group
of scientists, who were [sic experts in sea lion and seal viruses. But it
could still be some time before it was known exactly what had wiped out
almost half of this season's sea lion pup crop, he said.
Meanwhile, cruise liners, which are frequent visitors to the nearby
Campbell Islands, are waiting to see if they can help DOC staff stationed
there. Last week the Minister of Conservation, Nick Smith, closed the
Campbell Islands to visitors until more was known about the sea lion
plague. DOC Southern Islands manager Greg Lind said the cruise ship Kapitan
Klebnikov was is the area and was waiting to see if the crew could help by
taking staff off the islands. He was impressed with the support from cruise
ship operators. "We couldn't ask for better co-operation," Mr Lind said.
